WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.686 --> 00:00:15.822
Four years after arriving in the United States,
来美国四年以后，

2
00:00:15.846 --> 00:00:17.413
like any typical 16-year-old,
就像其他十六岁的人一样，

3
00:00:17.437 --> 00:00:20.188
I went to get my driver's permit.
我也去考了驾照。

4
00:00:20.212 --> 00:00:24.061
After I showed the clerk my immigration papers, my green card,
在给了那位办事员我的移民文件和绿卡后，

5
00:00:24.085 --> 00:00:28.470
she told me it was fake. "Don't come back here again," she said.
她跟我说“这是假的。别再来这儿了。”

6
00:00:29.141 --> 00:00:32.298
That's how I found out I was in America illegally.
我这才发现，原来自己是一名非法移民，

7
00:00:32.322 --> 00:00:34.854
And I'm still here illegally.
现在也依然是。

8
00:00:34.878 --> 00:00:36.433
I'm a journalist and filmmaker.
我是一位记者和制片人。

9
00:00:36.457 --> 00:00:38.308
I live in stories.
我的生活充满了各种各样的故事。

10
00:00:38.332 --> 00:00:39.779
And what I've learned
我发现，

11
00:00:39.803 --> 00:00:43.022
that what most people don't understand about immigration
大多数人对移民，

12
00:00:43.046 --> 00:00:46.335
is what they don't understand about themselves:
就和他们对自己的身份一样知之甚少：

13
00:00:46.359 --> 00:00:50.273
their families' old migration stories and the processes they had to go through
他们家族的移民故事，

14
00:00:50.297 --> 00:00:53.252
before green cards and walls even existed,
以及在绿卡和边境墙出现之前的移民流程，

15
00:00:53.276 --> 00:00:56.991
or what shaped their understanding of citizenship itself.
或者是什么形成了他们对公民身份的理解。

16
00:00:57.531 --> 00:00:59.288
I was born in the Philippines.
我出生在菲律宾。

17
00:00:59.312 --> 00:01:02.091
When I was 12, my mother sent me to live with her parents,
我十二岁的时候，妈妈把我送去和她的父母同住，

18
00:01:02.115 --> 00:01:03.336
my grandparents,
也就是我的外公外婆，

19
00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:05.821
or, as we say in Tagalog, lolo and lola.
加禄语中的称谓是洛洛和洛拉。

20
00:01:06.670 --> 00:01:08.871
Lolo's name was Teofilo.
洛洛的名字是特奧菲洛。

21
00:01:08.895 --> 00:01:13.411
When he legally emigrated to America and became a naturalized citizen,
他合法移民到了美国并成为公民后，

22
00:01:13.435 --> 00:01:16.478
he changed his name from Teofilo to Ted,
把自己的名字改成了泰德，

23
00:01:16.502 --> 00:01:19.979
after Ted Danson from the TV show "Cheers."
来自电视剧《欢乐酒店》中泰德·丹森（Ted Danson）的名字——

24
00:01:20.003 --> 00:01:22.110
Can't get any more American than that.
不能比这更有美国味儿了。

25
00:01:22.134 --> 00:01:26.038
Lolo's favorite song was Frank Sinatra's "My Way,"
洛洛最喜欢的歌是弗兰克·西纳特拉（Frank Sinatra）的《My Way》，

26
00:01:26.062 --> 00:01:31.427
and when it came to figuring out how to get his only grandson, me, to America,
当他想把我，他唯一的孙子送来美国时，

27
00:01:31.451 --> 00:01:33.086
he decided to do it his way.
他决定用自己的办法。

28
00:01:33.515 --> 00:01:37.494
According to Lolo, there was no easy and simple way to get me here,
他说，让我入境美国并不容易，

29
00:01:37.518 --> 00:01:41.374
so Lolo saved up 4,500 dollars --
所以他存了 4500 美金——

30
00:01:41.398 --> 00:01:43.468
that's a lot of money for a security guard
对一个保安来说，那是很多钱，

31
00:01:43.492 --> 00:01:45.661
who made no more than eight dollars an hour --
因为他一个小时只能赚 8 美元——

32
00:01:45.685 --> 00:01:47.178
to pay for the fake green card
他用这些钱给我买了个假绿卡，

33
00:01:47.202 --> 00:01:49.891
and for a smuggler to bring me to the US.
并请一个走私者把我带到了美国。

34
00:01:49.915 --> 00:01:51.408
So that's how I got here.
我就是这么到美国的。

35
00:01:51.432 --> 00:01:54.749
I can't tell you how many times people tell me that their ancestors
我记不清多少人告诉过我，

36
00:01:54.773 --> 00:01:57.261
came to America "the right way,"
他们的祖先是用“合法的方法”来到美国的。

37
00:01:57.285 --> 00:01:58.659
to which I remind them,
而我总会提醒他们，

38
00:01:58.683 --> 00:02:01.188
America's definition of "the right way"
美国对“合法的方法” 的定义

39
00:02:01.212 --> 00:02:05.829
has been changing ever since the first ship of settlers dropped anchor.
从第一批移民到来开始就在不断改变了。

40
00:02:06.718 --> 00:02:10.159
America as we know it is more than a piece of land,
美国不只是一片土地，

41
00:02:10.183 --> 00:02:14.046
particularly because the land that now makes up the United States of America
尤其因为构成美国的这片土地

42
00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:16.839
used to belong to other people in other countries.
曾经属于其他国家的其他人民。

43
00:02:17.346 --> 00:02:22.457
America as we know it is also more than a nation of immigrants.
我们所认识的美国也不只是个移民者的国家。

44
00:02:22.481 --> 00:02:26.391
There are two groups of Americans who are not immigrants:
有两群美国人不是移民：

45
00:02:26.415 --> 00:02:28.967
Native Americans, who were indigenous to this land
美洲土著，即美国的原住民，

46
00:02:28.991 --> 00:02:31.313
and who were killed in acts of genocide;
也是在种族灭绝中被屠杀的民族；

47
00:02:31.337 --> 00:02:35.152
and African Americans, who were kidnapped, shipped and enslaved
以及非洲裔美国人，一群被绑运、被迫为奴

48
00:02:35.176 --> 00:02:37.046
to build this country.
并建立了这个国家的人。

49
00:02:37.472 --> 00:02:41.289
America is, above all, an idea,
美国，在很大意义上，只是个理念——

50
00:02:41.313 --> 00:02:43.841
however unrealized and imperfect,
尽管尚未实现且并不完美——

51
00:02:43.865 --> 00:02:47.870
one that only exists because the first settlers came here freely
这个理念的存在只是因为来到这里的第一批定居者

52
00:02:47.894 --> 00:02:49.894
without worry of citizenship.
无须担心公民身份的问题。

53
00:02:50.289 --> 00:02:52.383
So, where did you come from?
所以，你从哪里来？

54
00:02:52.743 --> 00:02:53.962
How did you get here?
你是怎么来的？

55
00:02:54.471 --> 00:02:55.641
Who paid?
谁付了钱？

56
00:02:55.665 --> 00:02:58.436
All across America, in front of diverse audiences --
在美国各地，在不同的听众面前——

57
00:02:58.460 --> 00:02:59.967
conservatives and progressives,
无论是保守派还是激进派，

58
00:02:59.991 --> 00:03:02.017
high school students and senior citizens --
高中生还是老年人——

59
00:03:02.041 --> 00:03:03.457
I've asked those questions.
我都问过这些问题。

60
00:03:03.481 --> 00:03:06.233
As a person of color, I always get asked where I'm from,
作为一个有色人种，我经常被问从哪里来，

61
00:03:06.257 --> 00:03:08.708
as in, "Where are you from from?"
比如，“你老家是哪里的？”

62
00:03:08.732 --> 00:03:11.751
So I've asked white people where they're from from, too.
所以我也问白人，他们的老家是哪里的。

63
00:03:12.283 --> 00:03:14.719
After asking a student at the University of Georgia
在问了乔治亚大学的一名学生，

64
00:03:14.743 --> 00:03:15.943
where he was from,
他从哪里来之后，

65
00:03:15.967 --> 00:03:17.788
he said, "I'm American."
他说，“我是美国人。"

66
00:03:17.812 --> 00:03:20.443
"I know," I said, "but where are you from?"
我说， “我知道，但你从哪儿来的呢？”

67
00:03:20.826 --> 00:03:22.752
"I'm white," he replied.
他说， “我是白人。”

68
00:03:22.776 --> 00:03:25.667
"But white is not a country," I said.
我说， “ ‘白人’ 可不是一个国家。

69
00:03:25.691 --> 00:03:27.780
"Where are your ancestors from?"
你的祖先是从哪儿来的？”

70
00:03:28.248 --> 00:03:29.979
When he replied with a shrug,
他耸了耸肩，

71
00:03:30.003 --> 00:03:31.559
I said,
我又说，

72
00:03:31.583 --> 00:03:33.240
"Well, where did you come from?
“那么，你到底从哪儿来的？

73
00:03:33.264 --> 00:03:35.688
How did you get here? Who paid?"
你怎么来到这儿的？谁付的钱？”

74
00:03:36.463 --> 00:03:38.160
He couldn't answer.
他无法回答。

75
00:03:38.184 --> 00:03:41.011
I don't think you can talk about America as America
我觉得在讨论现在的美国时，

76
00:03:41.035 --> 00:03:44.356
without answering those three core questions.
我们没有办法回避这几个核心问题。

77
00:03:44.819 --> 00:03:47.694
Immigration is America's lifeline,
移民是美国的生命线，

78
00:03:47.718 --> 00:03:50.977
how this country has replenished itself for centuries,
是这个国家这几个世纪下来还一直流动新血液的原因。

79
00:03:51.001 --> 00:03:55.702
from the settlers and the revolutionaries who populated the original 13 colonies
从最初定居在十三个州的定居者和革命者，

80
00:03:55.726 --> 00:03:59.135
to the millions of immigrants, predominantly from Europe,
到数百万名主要来自欧洲，

81
00:03:59.159 --> 00:04:01.713
who relentlessly colonized this land.
并一直将殖民体系延续下来的移民者。

82
00:04:02.142 --> 00:04:04.733
Even though Native Americans were already here
尽管已经在这里的美国原住民

83
00:04:04.757 --> 00:04:08.211
and had their own tribal identities and ideas about citizenship,
有自己的部落和公民身份概念，

84
00:04:08.235 --> 00:04:13.889
they were not considered US citizens until the 1924 Indian Citizenship Act.
他们直到 1924 年的《印地安人公民法案 》颁布后才被认可为美国公民。

85
00:04:13.913 --> 00:04:18.996
The landmark 1964 Civil Rights Act that Black Americans fought for
美国黑人不断为之奋斗的、里程碑式的《1964 年民权法案》，

86
00:04:19.020 --> 00:04:23.298
inspired the 1965 Immigration and Nationality Act,
则催生了《1965 年移民和国籍法》，

87
00:04:23.322 --> 00:04:29.953
which ended America's race-based exclusionary system that had lasted for 40 years.
并终结了在美国持续 40 年之久的基于种族的排他制度。

88
00:04:30.389 --> 00:04:32.331
I could go on and on here,
这样的例子还有很多，

89
00:04:32.355 --> 00:04:35.327
but my point, my larger point, is this:
但我的要点是，

90
00:04:36.021 --> 00:04:37.786
How much do any of us,
我们中有多少人，

91
00:04:37.810 --> 00:04:40.595
whether immigrants of the past or the present,
不管是昔日还是现时的移民，

92
00:04:40.619 --> 00:04:43.898
know of these crucial parts of American history?
对美国这些关键历史有所了解？

93
00:04:43.922 --> 00:04:47.927
How much of this history makes up the actual US citizenship test?
这段历史在多大程度上构成了真正的美国公民资格测试？

94
00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:49.541
Have you ever seen it?
你们见过吗？

95
00:04:49.565 --> 00:04:51.282
It's a mostly oral test,
基本上大部分是口语测试，

96
00:04:51.306 --> 00:04:56.127
and government officers ask applicants up to 10 of the 100 questions.
政府官员会从一百个问题当中选出十个来问。

97
00:04:56.151 --> 00:04:59.950
To pass, applicants must get at least six answers right.
想要通过，至少要答对六个问题。

98
00:05:00.291 --> 00:05:02.150
I looked at the test recently,
我最近看过了测试题目，

99
00:05:02.174 --> 00:05:05.340
and I was aghast at the questions posed
并对问题内容，以及对这些

100
00:05:05.364 --> 00:05:09.503
and what constitutes acceptable answers to the glaring omissions.
明显被遗漏的合理答案感到十分惊讶。

101
00:05:09.527 --> 00:05:12.904
There's a question about the Statue of Liberty and where it is.
有一个关于自由女神像和它在哪里的问题，

102
00:05:12.928 --> 00:05:15.290
There's no question about Ellis Island,
却没有关于埃利斯岛，

103
00:05:15.314 --> 00:05:17.762
about the United States as an immigrant nation
以及美国作为一个移民国家

104
00:05:17.786 --> 00:05:20.889
and the countless anti-immigrant laws that were passed.
和它所通过的无数反移民法律的问题。

105
00:05:21.199 --> 00:05:23.753
There's nothing about Native American history.
完全没有关于美国原住民的问题。

106
00:05:24.070 --> 00:05:27.606
There's a question about what Martin Luther King, Jr. did,
有一个关于马丁·路德·金的问题，

107
00:05:27.630 --> 00:05:32.894
but largely, there's inadequate and irresponsible contexts about African Americans.
但在很大程度上，对非裔美国人的背景描述是非常不充分和不负责任的。

108
00:05:32.918 --> 00:05:34.108
Here's an example.
这里有个例子。

109
00:05:34.132 --> 00:05:38.330
Question number 74 under the American history section
美国历史部分的第74号问题

110
00:05:38.354 --> 00:05:43.844
asks applicants to "name one problem that led to the Civil War."
要求申请者 “列举一个导致美国内战的问题”。

111
00:05:43.868 --> 00:05:46.608
There are three acceptable answers:
有三个比较合理的答案：

112
00:05:47.204 --> 00:05:48.709
slavery,
奴隶制、

113
00:05:48.733 --> 00:05:50.541
states' rights,
州权

114
00:05:50.565 --> 00:05:52.885
economic reasons.
和经济原因。

115
00:05:53.219 --> 00:05:56.403
Did my Lola and Lolo get that question?
我的外公外婆被问到这个问题了吗？

116
00:05:56.427 --> 00:05:57.970
If they did get the question,
如果他们被问到这个问题，

117
00:05:57.994 --> 00:06:00.515
do they even understand the history behind it?
他们了解这背后的历史吗？

118
00:06:00.878 --> 00:06:03.070
How about my uncles and aunties and cousins
我的叔叔阿姨和堂兄弟们

119
00:06:03.094 --> 00:06:08.051
and millions of other immigrants who had to take that test to become Americans?
以及数百万参加这个测试成为美国人的其他移民呢？

120
00:06:08.442 --> 00:06:11.713
What do immigrants know about America before we get here?
在入境美国前，那些移民对美国了解多少？

121
00:06:12.259 --> 00:06:15.840
What kind of citizenship are we applying for?
我们在申请什么样的公民身份？

122
00:06:15.864 --> 00:06:20.224
And is that the same kind of citizenship we actually want to be a part of?
这跟我们想要获得的公民身份一样吗？

123
00:06:21.044 --> 00:06:23.935
Come to think of it -- I've been thinking a lot about this --
回想起来——我想过很多次——

124
00:06:23.959 --> 00:06:27.388
what does dignified citizenship look like?
有尊严的公民身份是什么样的？

125
00:06:27.412 --> 00:06:31.928
How can I ask for it when I just arrived here 26 years ago,
我到底应不应该得到这个公民身份？我来这里才 26 年，

126
00:06:31.952 --> 00:06:36.406
when Black and Native people who have been here in America for hundreds of years
而在美国生活了数百年的黑人和土著人

127
00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:38.378
are still waiting for theirs?
却依然在等待他们的身份。

128
00:06:38.853 --> 00:06:41.634
One of my favorite writers is Toni Morrison.
托尼·莫里森（ Toni Morrison）是我最喜欢的作家之一。

129
00:06:41.658 --> 00:06:46.119
In 1996, a year before I found out I was in the country illegally,
1996 年，也就是我发现自己非法移民身份的前一年，

130
00:06:46.143 --> 00:06:49.150
my eighth-grade class was assigned to read "The Bluest Eye,"
在八年级的课堂上，我们被要求阅读《最蓝的眼睛》(“The Bluest Eye”)，

131
00:06:49.174 --> 00:06:50.526
Morrison's first book.
莫里森的第一本书。

132
00:06:50.992 --> 00:06:55.251
Instantly, the book challenged me to ask hard questions.
突然间，这本书向我抛出了一些很难回答的问题。

133
00:06:55.275 --> 00:06:56.965
Why does Pecola Breedlove,
为什么皮克拉·布莱得拉夫（Pecola Breedlove）——

134
00:06:56.989 --> 00:06:59.513
this young Black girl at the center of the book,
书中年轻的黑人女主角——

135
00:06:59.537 --> 00:07:02.461
why did she want blue eyes?
想要蓝色的眼睛？

136
00:07:02.485 --> 00:07:04.175
Who told her to want it?
谁告诉她自己需要蓝眼睛？

137
00:07:04.587 --> 00:07:06.251
Why did she believe them?
她为什么会相信他们？

138
00:07:06.886 --> 00:07:10.196
Morrison said she wrote the book to illustrate what happens
莫里森说她写这本书，是为了解释当人们

139
00:07:10.220 --> 00:07:15.091
when a person surrenders to what she called "the master narrative."
向“主流叙事”屈服时会发生什么。

140
00:07:15.496 --> 00:07:21.967
"Definitions," Morrison said, "belong to the definers, not the defined."
莫里森说：“定义属于定义者，而不是被定义者。”

141
00:07:22.951 --> 00:07:25.037
Once I realized that I was here illegally,
在我意识到自己的非法移民身份后，

142
00:07:25.061 --> 00:07:30.659
I convinced myself that if I was not a legal citizen by birth or by law,
我说服自己，如果基于出生或按照法律，我不算是合法公民，

143
00:07:30.683 --> 00:07:33.915
another kind of citizenship was possible.
而另一种公民身份却是可能的。

144
00:07:33.939 --> 00:07:36.362
Citizenship as participation:
作为“参与者：的公民：

145
00:07:36.386 --> 00:07:37.609
I engage.
我参与其中。

146
00:07:37.633 --> 00:07:42.056
I engage with all kinds of Americans, even Americans who don't want me here.
我和各种各样的美国人打交道，甚至包括那些不希望我在这里的美国人。

147
00:07:42.595 --> 00:07:44.842
Citizenship as contribution:
作为“贡献者”的公民：

148
00:07:44.866 --> 00:07:48.655
I give back to my community in whatever ways I can.
我用一切可能的方法回馈我的社区。

149
00:07:48.679 --> 00:07:52.380
As an undocumented entrepreneur -- and yes, there is such a thing --
作为一个没有身份的企业家—— 是的，确实有这样的事情——

150
00:07:52.404 --> 00:07:55.014
I've employed many US citizens.
我雇佣了很多美国公民。

151
00:07:55.038 --> 00:07:57.575
Citizenship as education:
作为“接受教育”的公民：

152
00:07:57.599 --> 00:08:01.705
We can't wait for others to educate us about the past
我们不能等待其他人教授我们历史，

153
00:08:01.729 --> 00:08:03.605
and how we got to this present.
以及我们如何走到了今天。

154
00:08:03.629 --> 00:08:06.859
We have to educate ourselves and our circles.
我们得教育自己和我们的圈子。

155
00:08:07.597 --> 00:08:11.806
Citizenship as something greater than myself:
比自身的意义更深远的公民身份：

156
00:08:11.830 --> 00:08:14.635
We are, I think, individually and collectively,
我们，个人和集体，

157
00:08:14.659 --> 00:08:18.071
rewriting the master narrative of America.
在重写美国的主流叙事。

158
00:08:18.095 --> 00:08:21.634
The people who were once defined are now doing the defining.
过去被定义的人们现在成了定义者。

159
00:08:21.801 --> 00:08:24.484
They're asking the questions that need to be asked.
他们在问需要被问的问题。

160
00:08:24.508 --> 00:08:26.408
A core part of that redefinition
这个重新定义的核心是，

161
00:08:26.432 --> 00:08:29.557
is how we define not only who is an American
我们不仅会如何定义谁是美国人，

162
00:08:29.581 --> 00:08:31.777
but what constitutes citizenship.
还要定义是什么构成了公民身份。

163
00:08:32.097 --> 00:08:36.278
Which, to me, is our responsibility to each other.
这对我而言，是我们对彼此的责任。

164
00:08:37.096 --> 00:08:39.788
So consider your own personal narrative
所以，请思考下你自己的个人经历，

165
00:08:39.812 --> 00:08:41.010
and ask yourself:
并且问问自己：

166
00:08:41.634 --> 00:08:42.966
Where did you come from?
你来自哪里？

167
00:08:43.423 --> 00:08:44.658
How did you get here?
你是怎么来这里的？

168
00:08:45.546 --> 00:08:46.814
Who paid?
谁付的钱？